{"title_page": "Amitabh Mitra", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name         = Amitabh Mitra<br/>\u0985\u09ae\u09bf\u09a4\u09be\u09ad \u09ae\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\n| image        = Dr. Amitabh Mitra Physician Poet Artist South Africa.JPG\n| image_size   = 200px\n| caption      = Amitabh Mitra\n| birth_date   = \n| birth_place  = \n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| nationality  = South Africa\n| occupation   = Physician\n}}\n\n'''Amitabh Mitra''' ({{lang-bn|\u0985\u09ae\u09bf\u09a4\u09be\u09ad \u09ae\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0}}) is an Indian-born South African physician, poet and artist, whose paintings depict dramatised stick figures.\n\n==Education and career==\nMitra studied medicine and did postgraduate studies in [[orthopaedic surgery]] at the [[Gajara Raja Medical College]], [[Jiwaji University]], [[Gwalior]], India. He further specialised in [[aerospace medicine]] and [[family medicine]] at the [[University of Pretoria]], South Africa.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boloji.com/poetry/articles/025.htm | title=A Chat by Ramendra Kumar}}</ref>\n\nA practitioner of [[orthopaedic surgery]] and [[trauma surgery]], currently working at the Accident and Emergency unit of Cecilia Makiwane Hospital, [[Mdantsane]], South Africa, he has published five volumes of poetry and exhibited his poetry art. Mitra figures in the international roster of physician poets, a massive roster of ancient and contemporary poets / writers maintained by Daniel Bryant and assisted by Suzanne Poirer, Professor of Literature and Medical Education, [[University of Illinois]], USA<ref>{{cite web |url=http://library.med.nyu.edu/library/eresources/featuredcollections/bryant/bioshm.html#MITRA |title=Bryant Collection \u2013 Physician Roster |access-date=10 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110527010110/http://library.med.nyu.edu/library/eresources/featuredcollections/bryant/bioshm.html#MITRA |archive-date=27 May 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He represented South Africa at the World Literature Festival in [[Oslo]] 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://du-store-verden.no/index.php?topic=02/dsv2008/150/contributors&page=2 | title= Participation World Literature Festival, Oslo}}</ref>\n\n==Artistic influences==\n[[File:Mdantsane tembeka.jpg|thumb|Tembeka, A watercolor on a handmade paper by Amitabh Mitra]]\nA major section of Mitra's work on art and poetry is devoted to [[Gwalior]], where he grew up. His close friendship with the Maratha royal families resulted in his drawing a series of watercolour involving poetry which he exhibited in South Africa and [[India]]. ''A Slow Train to Gwalior'' is a coffee-table book of his art and poetry; a compact disc of his recitation with a backdrop of African traditional music was released by the Premier of Eastern Cape, [[Nosimo Balindlela]], and a short documentary film on his Gwalior poetry was shown at the [[Grahamstown]] [[National Arts Festival]] in 2009. In 2007 he was invited by the [[Sahitya Akademi]], New Delhi, where he presented his work to a poetry-loving audience.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-miscellaneous/article1177634.ece | title=The Hindu | location=Chennai, India | date=12 January 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ajthomas.in/gallery/?album=1&gallery=1 | title=At Sahitya Akademi, Delhi}}</ref>\n\n==As surgeon==\nMitra's work in trauma surgery took him to [[Bhutan]], where he worked at high-altitude hospitals of Chukha, Tsimalakha, Chimakothi and [[Thimphu]] under severe conditions. During these times he wrote poems about Bhutan, some of which were translated into French.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://poesiedumonde.com/category/asie/bhutan/ |title=Bhutan,Thimphu |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608040020/http://poesiedumonde.com/category/asie/bhutan/ |archive-date=8 June 2011 }}</ref> He wrote about his adventures in his search for the utopian Shangri La.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boloji.com/literature/00128.htm |title=The Search for Shangri-La |access-date=26 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114043224/http://boloji.com/literature/00128.htm |archive-date=14 January 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://psjk.homestead.com/Bhutan.html |title=In Bhutan}}</ref>\n[[Khushwant Singh]], the former editor of ''[[The Illustrated Weekly of India]]'' visited him to his hospital in Bhutan and wrote about him in his weekly columns, \"With Malice Towards One and All\" in the ''[[Times of India]]'' during the 1980s. Mitra later went to [[Arunachal Pradesh]], where he joined as an orthopaedic surgeon at [[Along, Arunachal Pradesh|Along]].\nHe joined as an orthopaedic surgeon at [[Bulawayo]], [[Zimbabwe]], in 1993. He lived in Bulawayo's Mzilikazi township and narrated his experiences during the time of political turmoil.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boloji.com/memoirs/053.htm |title=Remembering Zimbabwe of Old |access-date=26 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114201502/http://www.boloji.com/memoirs/053.htm |archive-date=14 January 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==As artist==\nHis present art is about the black township of [[Mdantsane]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.southafricanartists.com/showartist.asp?Code=MITRA001 |title= South African Artists}}</ref> where he works at the [[Cecilia Makiwane Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://desicritics.org/2009/03/01/103634.php |title=Cecilia Makiwane Hospital, Symbol of Hope and Courage in South Africa |access-date=26 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619232159/http://desicritics.org/2009/03/01/103634.php |archive-date=19 June 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=[[Daily Dispatch]] |url=http://www.dispatch.co.za/article.aspx?id=385484 |title=Journey through Mdantsane |last=Hennop |first=Jan |date=11 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615142054/http://www.dispatch.co.za/article.aspx?id=385484 |archive-date=15 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\n''Mdantsane Breathing'' is his book on the art and poetry of Mdantsane.\n\nDr. Mitra received on the 15 December 2018, the Provincial Eastern Cape Minister of Art and Culture's Special Award in the category of Fine Arts for his continued dedication to South African Arts\n\nDr. Mitra gifted the charcoal portrait done by him of Dr. [[Neil Aggett]] on 21 March 2019 at the 13th Annual Neil Aggett Memorial Lecture at Kingswood College, Grahamstown.The lecture takes place each year to celebrate the life of Neil Aggett and to honour his legacy. Dr Amitabh Mitra, was a special guest at this year\u2019s lecture as he presented the school with a charcoal drawing that he drew of Neil Aggett. This drawing is one very few visual representations of Aggett and will be displayed in the Kingswood College Museum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kingswoodcollege.com/2019/03/21/13th-annual-neil-aggett-memorial-lecture/|title=13th Annual Neil Aggett Memorial Lecture}}</ref>\n\nThe [[University of Cape Town]] honors and commemorates woman heroes of anti-apartheid struggle which includes [[Cecilia Makiwane]]. A charcoal portrait of [[Cecilia Makiwane]] done by Dr.Amitabh Mitra was exhibited at the Molly Blackburn Hall, University of Cape Town campus on the 19 September 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.news.uct.ac.za/article/-2019-09-20-rethinking-art-at-uct|title=Rethinking Art at UCT}}</ref>\n\n==As poet==\nHe translated the [[Bengali language|Bengali]] poetry of the late Prabhatkiran Bose, well known children's author in [[Bengal]] during the 1950s.<ref>{{ cite web |url=http://othervoicespoetry.org/vol38/bose/poetry.html |title=Like the bird who flew, Poetry of Prabhatkiran Bose |access-date=27 May 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001010531/http://othervoicespoetry.org/vol38/bose/poetry.html |archive-date=1 October 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{ cite web |url=http://othervoicespoetry.org/vol38/bose/bio.html |title=Translation of Prabhatkiran Bose's Bangla Poetry |access-date=10 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001010603/http://othervoicespoetry.org/vol38/bose/bio.html |archive-date=1 October 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nMitra's art and poetry on the township of Mdantsane, South Africa, was exhibited at the 2011 International Symposium for Poetry and Medicine and [[Hippocrates Prize for Poetry and Medicine]] Awards on Saturday, 7 May 2011, entitled ''Poems from Cecilia Makiwane Hospital''.<ref>{{ cite web |url=http://go.warwick.ac.uk/cpt/poetry/symp |title=2011 International Symposium for Poetry and Medicine, University of Warwick, UK}}</ref><ref>{{ cite web |url=http://www.writingworks.co.za/20110522/poetry-and-medicine/ |title=Poetry and Medicine}}</ref>\n\n''Splinters of a Mirage Dawn, An Anthology of Migrant Poetry of South Africa'' (co-edited with [[Naomi Nkealah]])  was short listed for the National Humanities and Social Sciences Award, South Africa, 2016.<ref>{{ cite web|url=http://poetsprintery.bookslive.co.za/blog/2016/04/11/daily-dispatch-south-africas-premier-daily-features-splinters-of-a-mirage-dawn-anthology-of-migrant-poetry-of-south-africa/|title=Daily Dispatch, South Africa\u2019s premier daily features Splinters of a Mirage Dawn, Anthology of Migrant Poetry of South Africa}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Poetry===\n*''Bithika''  \u2013 1978\n*''Ritual Silences'' \u2013 1980\n*''A Slow Train to [[Gwalior]]'' \u2013 2009\n*''Leaping the Lilac Sun'' \u2013 2009\n*''Mdantsane Breathing'' \u2013 2010\n*''Tonight, An Anthology of World Love Poetry'' \u2013 2008 (co-edited with [[Victoria Valentine]])\n*''Poems for Haiti, A South African Anthology'' (Foreword by Professor [[Peter Horn (poet)|Peter Horn]]) \u2013 2010\n*''Unbreaking the Rainbow, Voices of Protest from New South Africa'' (Foreword by [[Ela Gandhi]]) \u2013 2012\n*''Splinters of a Mirage Dawn, Anthology of Migrant Poetry from South Africa'' (co-edited with [[Naomi Nkealah]]) (Art by [[Arpana Caur]]) \u2013 2013\n*''Our Little Black Book of Ills, Poetry Anthology, Four Poets Share Expressions of Grief''(with [[Victoria Valentine]][[Lynda G Bullerwell]][[jacob erin-cilberto]]) - 2015\n*''Stranger than a Sun, Poems and Drawings of Gwalior'' - 2015\n*''Trainstorm, An Anthology of Alternative Train Poetry'' - 2016\n\n===Editor===\n*''A Hudson View'', A Quarterly Print Poetry Journal<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hudsonview.us |title=A Hudson View Poetry Digest}}</ref>\n*''Inyathi'', A Journal on South African Arts<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.buffalocity.gov.za/news2008/aug/aug28_inyathi.stm |work=buffalocity.gov.za |date=28 August 2008 |title=Inyathi Journal trumpets its success |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100929080645/http://buffalocity.gov.za/news2008/aug/aug28_inyathi.stm |archive-date=29 September 2010 }}</ref>\n\n===Compact disc of poetry and music===\n*''A Slow Train to Gwalior'' \u2013 2007\n\n====Appearances in the following poetry Anthologies====\n* ''Travelogue : The Grand Indian Express'' (2018) ed. by Dr. Ananad Kumar and published by Authorspress, [[New Delhi]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.amitabhmitra.com}}\n* {{Cite web |work= Lila Interactions |url=http://www.lilainteractions.in/gandhi/ | title= Gandhi Experimenting With | date=3 October 2014}}\n* {{Cite web |work=Books Live |url=http://poetsprintery.bookslive.co.za |title= Chirikure Chirikure reviews Splinters of a Mirage Dawn|date=30 October 2013}}\n* {{cite news|work=[[Daily Dispatch]] |url=http://www.dispatch.za.com/news/article/3646 |title=East London Doctor Launches Poetry Book |last=Shanaaz Prince |date=6 July 2012 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* {{cite news|work=[[Daily Dispatch]] |url=http://www.dispatch.co.za/article.aspx?id=243665 |title=EL medical officer is an artist and a poet |last=Staff |date=2 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615142114/http://www.dispatch.co.za/article.aspx?id=243665 |archive-date=15 June 2011 }}\n* {{Cite news |work=The Post |url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G1-199185932.html |title=Mitra,Doctor of Poetry |date=6 May 2009 |first=Tasnim |last=Langry}}\n* {{cite news |work=The Post |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-179023301.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103102501/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-179023301.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 November 2012 |title=The doctor who indulges in paint and poems |date=14 May 2008 |first=Candice |last=Soobramoney}}\n* {{Cite web |work=African Writing Online ISSN 1754-6672 |url=http://african-writing.com/hol/amitabhmitra.htm |title=Amitabh Mitra |date=December/January 2008}}\n* {{Cite web |work=Other Voices Poetry |url=http://www.othervoicespoetry.org/vol19/mitra/poetry.html |title=A Slow Train to Gwalior Volume 19 |date=30 November 2008 |access-date=27 May 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721073228/http://www.othervoicespoetry.org/vol19/mitra/poetry.html |archive-date=21 July 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n* {{Cite web |work=Subtle Tea |url=http://www.subtletea.com/amitabhmitrapoetry.htm |title=Subtle Tea, Poetry by Amitabh Mitra |year=2006}}\n*{{Cite web |work=Slow Trains |url=http://www.slowtrains.com/vol5issue2/mitravol5issue2.html |title=Slow Trains Literary Journal, Zubeida |year=2005}}\n*{{Cite web |work= [[Daily Dispatch]]|url=http://www.pressreader.com/south-africa/daily-dispatch/20160926/281539405439121 |title= Solo Art Show Demonstrates Doctor's Versatility |date=26 September 2016 |first=Vuvu |last=Vena}}\n*{{Cite web |work= [[Go & Express Community Newspaper]]|url=http://showme.co.za/east-london/news/mitra-acrylic-works-for-coach-house/ |title=Mitra Acrylic Works for Coach House |date=23 September 2016}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitra, Amitabh}}\n[[Category:University of Pretoria alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African poets]]\n[[Category:People from Gwalior]]\n[[Category:English-language poets from India]]\n[[Category:South African people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Jiwaji University alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Bengali male poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Bengali poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Bengali poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person \n| name         = Amitabh Mitra<br/>\u0985\u09ae\u09bf\u09a4\u09be\u09ad \u09ae\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\n| image        = Dr. Amitabh Mitra Physician Poet Artist South Africa.JPG\n| image_size   = 200px\n| caption      = Amitabh Mitra\n| birth_date   = \n| birth_place  = \n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| nationality  = South Africa\n| occupation   = Physician\n}}\n\n'''Amitabh Mitra''' ({{lang-bn|\u0985\u09ae\u09bf\u09a4\u09be\u09ad \u09ae\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0}}) is an Indian-born South African physician, poet and artist, whose paintings depict dramatised stick figures.\n\n==Education and career==\nMitra studied medicine and did postgraduate studies in [[orthopaedic surgery]] at the [[Gajara Raja Medical College]], [[Jiwaji University]], [[Gwalior]], India. He further specialised in [[aerospace medicine]] and [[family medicine]] at the [[University of Pretoria]], South Africa.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boloji.com/poetry/articles/025.htm | title=A Chat by Ramendra Kumar}}</ref>\n\nA practitioner of [[orthopaedic surgery]] and [[trauma surgery]], currently working at the Accident and Emergency unit of Cecilia Makiwane Hospital, [[Mdantsane]], South Africa, he has published five volumes of poetry and exhibited his poetry art. Mitra figures in the international roster of physician poets, a massive roster of ancient and contemporary poets / writers maintained by Daniel Bryant and assisted by Suzanne Poirer, Professor of Literature and Medical Education, [[University of Illinois]], USA<ref>{{cite web |url=http://library.med.nyu.edu/library/eresources/featuredcollections/bryant/bioshm.html#MITRA |title=Bryant Collection \u2013 Physician Roster |access-date=10 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110527010110/http://library.med.nyu.edu/library/eresources/featuredcollections/bryant/bioshm.html#MITRA |archive-date=27 May 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He represented South Africa at the World Literature Festival in [[Oslo]] 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://du-store-verden.no/index.php?topic=02/dsv2008/150/contributors&page=2 | title= Participation World Literature Festival, Oslo}}</ref>\n\n==Artistic influences==\n[[File:Mdantsane tembeka.jpg|thumb|Tembeka, A watercolor on a handmade paper by Amitabh Mitra]]\nA major section of Mitra's work on art and poetry is devoted to [[Gwalior]], where he grew up. His close friendship with the Maratha royal families resulted in his drawing a series of watercolour involving poetry which he exhibited in South Africa and [[India]]. ''A Slow Train to Gwalior'' is a coffee-table book of his art and poetry; a compact disc of his recitation with a backdrop of African traditional music was released by the Premier of Eastern Cape, [[Nosimo Balindlela]], and a short documentary film on his Gwalior poetry was shown at the [[Grahamstown]] [[National Arts Festival]] in 2009. In 2007 he was invited by the [[Sahitya Akademi]], New Delhi, where he presented his work to a poetry-loving audience.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-miscellaneous/article1177634.ece | title=The Hindu | location=Chennai, India | date=12 January 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ajthomas.in/gallery/?album=1&gallery=1 | title=At Sahitya Akademi, Delhi}}</ref>\n\n==As surgeon==\nMitra's work in trauma surgery took him to [[Bhutan]], where he worked at high-altitude hospitals of Chukha, Tsimalakha, Chimakothi and [[Thimphu]] under severe conditions. During these times he wrote poems about Bhutan, some of which were translated into French.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://poesiedumonde.com/category/asie/bhutan/ |title=Bhutan,Thimphu |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608040020/http://poesiedumonde.com/category/asie/bhutan/ |archive-date=8 June 2011 }}</ref> He wrote about his adventures in his search for the utopian Shangri La.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boloji.com/literature/00128.htm |title=The Search for Shangri-La |access-date=26 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114043224/http://boloji.com/literature/00128.htm |archive-date=14 January 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://psjk.homestead.com/Bhutan.html |title=In Bhutan}}</ref>\n[[Khushwant Singh]], the former editor of ''[[The Illustrated Weekly of India]]'' visited him to his hospital in Bhutan and wrote about him in his weekly columns, \"With Malice Towards One and All\" in the ''[[Times of India]]'' during the 1980s. Mitra later went to [[Arunachal Pradesh]], where he joined as an orthopaedic surgeon at [[Along, Arunachal Pradesh|Along]].\nHe joined as an orthopaedic surgeon at [[Bulawayo]], [[Zimbabwe]], in 1993. He lived in Bulawayo's Mzilikazi township and narrated his experiences during the time of political turmoil.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boloji.com/memoirs/053.htm |title=Remembering Zimbabwe of Old |access-date=26 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114201502/http://www.boloji.com/memoirs/053.htm |archive-date=14 January 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==As artist==\nHis present art is about the black township of [[Mdantsane]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.southafricanartists.com/showartist.asp?Code=MITRA001 |title= South African Artists}}</ref> where he works at the [[Cecilia Makiwane Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://desicritics.org/2009/03/01/103634.php |title=Cecilia Makiwane Hospital, Symbol of Hope and Courage in South Africa |access-date=26 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619232159/http://desicritics.org/2009/03/01/103634.php |archive-date=19 June 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=[[Daily Dispatch]] |url=http://www.dispatch.co.za/article.aspx?id=385484 |title=Journey through Mdantsane |last=Hennop |first=Jan |date=11 March 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615142054/http://www.dispatch.co.za/article.aspx?id=385484 |archive-date=15 June 2011 }}</ref>\n\n''Mdantsane Breathing'' is his book on the art and poetry of Mdantsane.\n\nDr. Mitra received on the 15 December 2018, the Provincial Eastern Cape Minister of Art and Culture's Special Award in the category of Fine Arts for his continued dedication to South African Arts\n\nDr. Mitra gifted the charcoal portrait done by him of Dr. [[Neil Aggett]] on 21 March 2019 at the 13th Annual Neil Aggett Memorial Lecture at Kingswood College, Grahamstown.The lecture takes place each year to celebrate the life of Neil Aggett and to honour his legacy. Dr Amitabh Mitra, was a special guest at this year\u2019s lecture as he presented the school with a charcoal drawing that he drew of Neil Aggett. This drawing is one very few visual representations of Aggett and will be displayed in the Kingswood College Museum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kingswoodcollege.com/2019/03/21/13th-annual-neil-aggett-memorial-lecture/|title=13th Annual Neil Aggett Memorial Lecture}}</ref>\n\nThe [[University of Cape Town]] honors and commemorates woman heroes of anti-apartheid struggle which includes [[Cecilia Makiwane]]. A charcoal portrait of [[Cecilia Makiwane]] done by Dr.Amitabh Mitra was exhibited at the Molly Blackburn Hall, University of Cape Town campus on the 19 September 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.news.uct.ac.za/article/-2019-09-20-rethinking-art-at-uct|title=Rethinking Art at UCT}}</ref>\n\n==As poet==\nHe translated the [[Bengali language|Bengali]] poetry of the late Prabhatkiran Bose, well known children's author in [[Bengal]] during the 1950s.<ref>{{ cite web |url=http://othervoicespoetry.org/vol38/bose/poetry.html |title=Like the bird who flew, Poetry of Prabhatkiran Bose |access-date=27 May 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001010531/http://othervoicespoetry.org/vol38/bose/poetry.html |archive-date=1 October 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{ cite web |url=http://othervoicespoetry.org/vol38/bose/bio.html |title=Translation of Prabhatkiran Bose's Bangla Poetry |access-date=10 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001010603/http://othervoicespoetry.org/vol38/bose/bio.html |archive-date=1 October 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nMitra's art and poetry on the township of Mdantsane, South Africa, was exhibited at the 2011 International Symposium for Poetry and Medicine and [[Hippocrates Prize for Poetry and Medicine]] Awards on Saturday, 7 May 2011, entitled ''Poems from Cecilia Makiwane Hospital''.<ref>{{ cite web |url=http://go.warwick.ac.uk/cpt/poetry/symp |title=2011 International Symposium for Poetry and Medicine, University of Warwick, UK}}</ref><ref>{{ cite web |url=http://www.writingworks.co.za/20110522/poetry-and-medicine/ |title=Poetry and Medicine}}</ref>\n\n''Splinters of a Mirage Dawn, An Anthology of Migrant Poetry of South Africa'' (co-edited with [[Naomi Nkealah]])  was short listed for the National Humanities and Social Sciences Award, South Africa, 2016.<ref>{{ cite web|url=http://poetsprintery.bookslive.co.za/blog/2016/04/11/daily-dispatch-south-africas-premier-daily-features-splinters-of-a-mirage-dawn-anthology-of-migrant-poetry-of-south-africa/|title=Daily Dispatch, South Africa\u2019s premier daily features Splinters of a Mirage Dawn, Anthology of Migrant Poetry of South Africa}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Poetry===\n*''Bithika''  \u2013 1978\n*''Ritual Silences'' \u2013 1980\n*''A Slow Train to [[Gwalior]]'' \u2013 2009\n*''Leaping the Lilac Sun'' \u2013 2009\n*''Mdantsane Breathing'' \u2013 2010\n*''Tonight, An Anthology of World Love Poetry'' \u2013 2008 (co-edited with [[Victoria Valentine]])\n*''Poems for Haiti, A South African Anthology'' (Foreword by Professor [[Peter Horn (poet)|Peter Horn]]) \u2013 2010\n*''Unbreaking the Rainbow, Voices of Protest from New South Africa'' (Foreword by [[Ela Gandhi]]) \u2013 2012\n*''Splinters of a Mirage Dawn, Anthology of Migrant Poetry from South Africa'' (co-edited with [[Naomi Nkealah]]) (Art by [[Arpana Caur]]) \u2013 2013\n*''Our Little Black Book of Ills, Poetry Anthology, Four Poets Share Expressions of Grief''(with [[Victoria Valentine]][[Lynda G Bullerwell]][[jacob erin-cilberto]]) - 2015\n*''Stranger than a Sun, Poems and Drawings of Gwalior'' - 2015\n*''Trainstorm, An Anthology of Alternative Train Poetry'' - 2016\n\n===Editor===\n*''A Hudson View'', A Quarterly Print Poetry Journal<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hudsonview.us |title=A Hudson View Poetry Digest}}</ref>\n*''Inyathi'', A Journal on South African Arts<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.buffalocity.gov.za/news2008/aug/aug28_inyathi.stm |work=buffalocity.gov.za |date=28 August 2008 |title=Inyathi Journal trumpets its success |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100929080645/http://buffalocity.gov.za/news2008/aug/aug28_inyathi.stm |archive-date=29 September 2010 }}</ref>\n\n===Compact disc of poetry and music===\n*''A Slow Train to Gwalior'' \u2013 2007\n\n====Appearances in the following poetry Anthologies====\n* ''Travelogue : The Grand Indian Express'' (2018) ed. by Dr. Ananad Kumar and published by Authorspress, [[New Delhi]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.amitabhmitra.com}}\n* {{Cite web |work= Lila Interactions |url=http://www.lilainteractions.in/gandhi/ | title= Gandhi Experimenting With | date=3 October 2014}}\n* {{Cite web |work=Books Live |url=http://poetsprintery.bookslive.co.za |title= Chirikure Chirikure reviews Splinters of a Mirage Dawn|date=30 October 2013}}\n* {{cite news|work=[[Daily Dispatch]] |url=http://www.dispatch.za.com/news/article/3646 |title=East London Doctor Launches Poetry Book |last=Shanaaz Prince |date=6 July 2012 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* {{cite news|work=[[Daily Dispatch]] |url=http://www.dispatch.co.za/article.aspx?id=243665 |title=EL medical officer is an artist and a poet |last=Staff |date=2 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615142114/http://www.dispatch.co.za/article.aspx?id=243665 |archive-date=15 June 2011 }}\n* {{Cite news |work=The Post |url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G1-199185932.html |title=Mitra,Doctor of Poetry |date=6 May 2009 |first=Tasnim |last=Langry}}\n* {{cite news |work=The Post |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-179023301.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103102501/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-179023301.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 November 2012 |title=The doctor who indulges in paint and poems |date=14 May 2008 |first=Candice |last=Soobramoney}}\n* {{Cite web |work=African Writing Online ISSN 1754-6672 |url=http://african-writing.com/hol/amitabhmitra.htm |title=Amitabh Mitra |date=December/January 2008}}\n* {{Cite web |work=Other Voices Poetry |url=http://www.othervoicespoetry.org/vol19/mitra/poetry.html |title=A Slow Train to Gwalior Volume 19 |date=30 November 2008 |access-date=27 May 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721073228/http://www.othervoicespoetry.org/vol19/mitra/poetry.html |archive-date=21 July 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n* {{Cite web |work=Subtle Tea |url=http://www.subtletea.com/amitabhmitrapoetry.htm |title=Subtle Tea, Poetry by Amitabh Mitra |year=2006}}\n*{{Cite web |work=Slow Trains |url=http://www.slowtrains.com/vol5issue2/mitravol5issue2.html |title=Slow Trains Literary Journal, Zubeida |year=2005}}\n*{{Cite web |work= [[Daily Dispatch]]|url=http://www.pressreader.com/south-africa/daily-dispatch/20160926/281539405439121 |title= Solo Art Show Demonstrates Doctor's Versatility |date=26 September 2016 |first=Vuvu |last=Vena}}\n*{{Cite web |work= [[Go & Express Community Newspaper]]|url=http://showme.co.za/east-london/news/mitra-acrylic-works-for-coach-house/ |title=Mitra Acrylic Works for Coach House |date=23 September 2016}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitra, Amitabh}}\n[[Category:University of Pretoria alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African poets]]\n[[Category:People from Gwalior]]\n[[Category:English-language poets from India]]\n[[Category:South African people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Jiwaji University alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Bengali male poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Bengali poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Bengali poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amitabh_Mitra"}
{"title_page": "James Matthews (writer)", "text_new": "{{for|the New Zealand writer|Jim Matthews (writer)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use South African English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = James Matthews\n| awards =\n| image =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1929|5|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Bo-Kaap]], [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]]\n| occupation = Poet\n| nationality = [[South Africa]]n\n| influences =\n| influenced =\n}}\n\n'''James Matthews''' (born 24 May 1929) is a [[South African people|South African]] poet, writer and publisher. During the [[Apartheid]] era his poetry was banned, and Matthews was detained by the government in 1976 and for 13 years was denied a passport.\n\n==Biography==\nJames David Matthews was born to working-class parents in [[District Six]], [[Cape Town]], on 29 May 1929.<ref name=SAHO>[http://www.sahistory.org.za/people/james-david-matthews \"James David Matthews\"], South African History Online.</ref> He attended Prestwich Primary School and then went on to [[Trafalgar High School (Cape Town)|Trafalgar High School]] in Cape Town. He has said:\n<blockquote>\"I grew up in a household where there were no shelves filled with books. My father was illiterate and my mother read ''Oracle'' and ''Miracle'', two thin paperbacks from the United Kingdom which could hardly be considered as literature....\n\nI was almost 14 and in standard eight (grade 10) when we were asked to write a composition. It is now termed creative writing. I will never forget the name of our English teacher \u2013 Miss Meredith. She announced to the class that I had written a short story and not a composition. She marked it 21, one mark above the accepted 20 and informed the class that I was a writer.\n\nMy introduction to a library was one of wonderment. I was a messenger at the ''Cape Times'' and a reporter asked me to take her books to the library. I was confronted by row upon row of stalls stacked with books. My eyes travelled along the lines of names and titles. None of them were known to me. My reading at that stage was limited to [[James Hadley Chase]]. Tentatively I asked the reporter if I could take out a book for myself when I returned her books the following time. She agreed and a new world opened to me because public libraries were then exclusively for the benefit of whites....<ref name=M&G>James Matthews, [http://mg.co.za/article/2016-04-13-how-reading-can-change-your-life \"How reading can change your life\"], ''Mail & Guardian'', 15 April 2016.</ref></blockquote>\n\nAfter leaving school he had a number of jobs, including as newspaper boy, office messenger, clerk and telephonist, and after publishing his first writings in 1946, when he was aged 17, he found work as a journalist, over the years contributing to various national publications such as the ''Golden City Post'', ''[[The Cape Times]]'', and ''[[Drum magazine|Drum]]'', as well as the independent community newspaper ''The Muslim News''.<ref name=SAHO />\n\nMatthews through his poetry became \"a leading articulator of the [[Black Consciousness]] philosophy\".<ref name=SAHO /> In 1972 his first collection, ''Cry Rage'' (co-authored with Gladys Thomas), was published. It was banned by the [[apartheid]] regime \u2014 the first poetry collection thus targeted \u2014 as would also happen to most of his later works.<ref name=SAHO /> Matthews was detained by the government in 1976, and was denied a passport for 13 years.<ref name=PA>[http://www.poetryarchive.org/poet/james-matthews \"About James Matthews\"], The Poetry Archive.</ref>\n\nHe established the first black-founded art gallery in South Africa (Gallery Afrique) in 1972, and the first black-owned publishing house, BLAC (standing for Black Literature Arts and Culture), 1974\u201391, which closed as a result of constant government harassment.<ref>[http://www.cca.ukzn.ac.za/index.php/component/content/article?id=716:niels-hav-denmark \"James Matthews (South Africa)\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216160235/http://www.cca.ukzn.ac.za/index.php/component/content/article?id=716:niels-hav-denmark |date=16 February 2017 }}, Centre for Creative Arts, University of Kwazulu-Natal, 3 November 2014.</ref><ref name=PA /><ref>Paul Maylam, [https://www.ru.ac.za/media/rhodesuniversity/content/alumni/documents/CITATION%20FOR%20JAMES%20MATTHEWS%20(2).pdf \"Citation for James Matthews\"] (Honorary graduand, Rhodes University, 31 March 2016).</ref> In 2000, he founded the publishing house Realities.\n\nHe is a founding member and the patron of the [[Congress of South African Writers]] since its inception in 1987.\n\n==Honours and recognition==\n\nAwards that Matthews has received include the Woza Afrika Award (1978), Kwaza Honours List \u2013 Black Arts Celebration, [[Chicago]] (1979) and the Freeman of the towns of [[Lehrte]] and Nienburg, Germany (1982).<ref name=PA />\n\nHe was the recipient of a national honour, the [[Order of Ikhamanga]] (Silver), in December 2004,<ref>[http://www.thepresidency.gov.za/pebble.asp?relid=7754 \"The Order of Ikhamanga\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306205805/http://www.thepresidency.gov.za/pebble.asp?relid=7754 |date=6 March 2016 }}, The Presidency, Republic of South Africa.</ref> for \"His excellent achievements in literature, contributing to journalism and his inspirational commitment to the struggle for a non-racial South Africa.\"<ref>[http://www.thepresidency.gov.za/pebble.asp?relid=7779 \"James  Matthews (1929 - ), The Order of Ikhamanga in Silver\"], The Presidency, Republic of South Africa.</ref><ref>Aziz Matthews,[https://seekingthesoapbox.wordpress.com/2014/05/15/james-matthews-struggle-poet-and-laureate-of-national-honours/ \"James Matthews: Struggle poet and laureate of National Honours\"], Seeking the Soapbox, 15 May 2014.</ref>\n\nOn 11 March 2013 he received an honorary doctorate from the [[University of the Western Cape]].<ref>[https://www.uwc.ac.za/Pages/2013-March-Graduation.aspx \"UWC honours struggle poet and sports administrator at its Summer Graduation\"], 2013 March Graduation, University of the Western Cape.</ref> [[Rhodes University]] in [[Grahamstown]] also awarded him an honorary doctorate, on 31 March 2016.<ref>[https://www.ru.ac.za/latestnews/acatwhogotluckywithwords.html \"A Cat Who Got Lucky With Words\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806074305/https://www.ru.ac.za/latestnews/acatwhogotluckywithwords.html |date=6 August 2016 }}, Rhodes University, 31 March 2016.</ref><ref>Yazeed Kamaldien, [https://www.ru.ac.za/studentlife/rhodesnews/articles/capepoeturgesuniversitiestoteachhiswork.html \"Cape poet urges universities to teach his work\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806113803/https://www.ru.ac.za/studentlife/rhodesnews/articles/capepoeturgesuniversitiestoteachhiswork.html |date=6 August 2016 }}, ''Studentlife'', Rhodes University, 30 March 2016.</ref>\n\n===Film===\nIn 2014, Shelley Barry's documentary ''Diaries of A Dissident Poet'', a film profiling James Matthews,<ref>Rustum Kozain, [http://africasacountry.com/2014/07/james-matthews-being-james-matthews/ \"James Matthews being James Matthews\"], Africa is a Country, 31 July 2014.</ref> premiered at the Encounters Film Festival in South Africa.<ref>http://www.encounters.co.za/</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* Woza Afrika Award (1978)\n* Kwaza Honours List \u2014 Black Arts Celebration, Chicago, U.S.A. (1979)\n* Freeman of Lehrte and Nienburg, Germany (1982)\n* National Order of Ikhamanga, South African government (2004)\n* Honorary doctorate, University of the Western Cape (2013)\n* Honorary doctorate, Rhodes University (2016)\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Poetry===\n*''Cry Rage'' (1972), Spro-Cas Publications\n*''Black Voices Shout'' (1974)\n*''Pass me a Meatball, Jones'' (1977)\n*''No Time for Dreams'' (1981), BLAC Publications\n*''Poisoned Wells and Other Delights'' (1990), BLAC Publications\n*''Flames and Flowers'' (2000), Realities\n*''Poems from a Prison Cell'' (2002), Realities\n*''Age is a Beautiful Phase'' (2008), Realities\n*''Gently Stirs My Soul'' (2015), Rhodes University\n\n===Short stories===\n*''The Park and Other Stories'' (1983), Ravan Press\n\n===Novels===\n*''The Party is Over'' (1997), Kwela\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ukzn.ac.za/cca/PoetryAfrica2002bios15.html#JAMES%20MATTHEWS Poetry Africa UKZN entry]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110604093719/http://www.info.gov.za/aboutgovt/orders/2004/matthews.htm SA Government page]\n* Mphutlane Wa Bofelo, [http://botsotso.org.za/2013/05/james-matthews-still-kicking-butt-77/ \"James Matthews: Still Kicking Butt @ 77\"], ''Botsotso'', 6 May 2013.\n* James Matthews, [http://mg.co.za/article/2016-04-13-how-reading-can-change-your-life \"How reading can change your life\"], ''Mail & Guardian'', 15 April 2016.\n*  Paul Maylam, [https://www.ru.ac.za/media/rhodesuniversity/content/alumni/documents/CITATION%20FOR%20JAMES%20MATTHEWS%20(2).pdf \"Citation for James Matthews\"] (Honorary graduand, Rhodes University, 31 March 2016).\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Matthews, James}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Ikhamanga]]\n[[Category:Anti-apartheid activists]]\n[[Category:International Writing Program alumni]]\n[[Category:South African publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:South African journalists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Cape Town]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the New Zealand writer|Jim Matthews (writer)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use South African English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = James Matthews\n| awards =\n| image =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1929|5|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Bo-Kaap]], [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]]\n| occupation = Poet\n| nationality = [[South Africa]]n\n| influences =\n| influenced =\n}}\n\n'''James Matthews''' (born 24 May 1929) is a [[South African people|South African]] poet, writer and publisher. During the [[Apartheid]] era his poetry was banned, and Matthews was detained by the government in 1976 and for 13 years was denied a passport.\n\n==Biography==\nJames David Matthews was born to working-class parents in [[District Six]], [[Cape Town]], on 29 May 1929.<ref name=SAHO>[http://www.sahistory.org.za/people/james-david-matthews \"James David Matthews\"], South African History Online.</ref> He attended Prestwich Primary School and then went on to [[Trafalgar High School (Cape Town)|Trafalgar High School]] in Cape Town. He has said:\n<blockquote>\"I grew up in a household where there were no shelves filled with books. My father was illiterate and my mother read ''Oracle'' and ''Miracle'', two thin paperbacks from the United Kingdom which could hardly be considered as literature....\n\nI was almost 14 and in standard eight (grade 10) when we were asked to write a composition. It is now termed creative writing. I will never forget the name of our English teacher \u2013 Miss Meredith. She announced to the class that I had written a short story and not a composition. She marked it 21, one mark above the accepted 20 and informed the class that I was a writer.\n\nMy introduction to a library was one of wonderment. I was a messenger at the ''Cape Times'' and a reporter asked me to take her books to the library. I was confronted by row upon row of stalls stacked with books. My eyes travelled along the lines of names and titles. None of them were known to me. My reading at that stage was limited to [[James Hadley Chase]]. Tentatively I asked the reporter if I could take out a book for myself when I returned her books the following time. She agreed and a new world opened to me because public libraries were then exclusively for the benefit of whites....<ref name=M&G>James Matthews, [http://mg.co.za/article/2016-04-13-how-reading-can-change-your-life \"How reading can change your life\"], ''Mail & Guardian'', 15 April 2016.</ref></blockquote>\n\nAfter leaving school he had a number of jobs, including as newspaper boy, office messenger, clerk and telephonist, and after publishing his first writings in 1946, when he was aged 17, he found work as a journalist, over the years contributing to various national publications such as the ''Golden City Post'', ''[[The Cape Times]]'', and ''[[Drum magazine|Drum]]'', as well as the independent community newspaper ''The Muslim News''.<ref name=SAHO />\n\nMatthews through his poetry became \"a leading articulator of the [[Black Consciousness]] philosophy\".<ref name=SAHO /> In 1972 his first collection, ''Cry Rage'' (co-authored with Gladys Thomas), was published. It was banned by the [[apartheid]] regime \u2014 the first poetry collection thus targeted \u2014 as would also happen to most of his later works.<ref name=SAHO /> Matthews was detained by the government in 1976, and was denied a passport for 13 years.<ref name=PA>[http://www.poetryarchive.org/poet/james-matthews \"About James Matthews\"], The Poetry Archive.</ref>\n\nHe established the first black-founded art gallery in South Africa (Gallery Afrique) in 1972, and the first black-owned publishing house, BLAC (standing for Black Literature Arts and Culture), 1974\u201391, which closed as a result of constant government harassment.<ref>[http://www.cca.ukzn.ac.za/index.php/component/content/article?id=716:niels-hav-denmark \"James Matthews (South Africa)\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216160235/http://www.cca.ukzn.ac.za/index.php/component/content/article?id=716:niels-hav-denmark |date=16 February 2017 }}, Centre for Creative Arts, University of Kwazulu-Natal, 3 November 2014.</ref><ref name=PA /><ref>Paul Maylam, [https://www.ru.ac.za/media/rhodesuniversity/content/alumni/documents/CITATION%20FOR%20JAMES%20MATTHEWS%20(2).pdf \"Citation for James Matthews\"] (Honorary graduand, Rhodes University, 31 March 2016).</ref> In 2000, he founded the publishing house Realities.\n\nHe is a founding member and the patron of the [[Congress of South African Writers]] since its inception in 1987.\n\n==Honours and recognition==\n\nAwards that Matthews has received include the Woza Afrika Award (1978), Kwaza Honours List \u2013 Black Arts Celebration, [[Chicago]] (1979) and the Freeman of the towns of [[Lehrte]] and Nienburg, Germany (1982).<ref name=PA />\n\nHe was the recipient of a national honour, the [[Order of Ikhamanga]] (Silver), in December 2004,<ref>[http://www.thepresidency.gov.za/pebble.asp?relid=7754 \"The Order of Ikhamanga\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306205805/http://www.thepresidency.gov.za/pebble.asp?relid=7754 |date=6 March 2016 }}, The Presidency, Republic of South Africa.</ref> for \"His excellent achievements in literature, contributing to journalism and his inspirational commitment to the struggle for a non-racial South Africa.\"<ref>[http://www.thepresidency.gov.za/pebble.asp?relid=7779 \"James  Matthews (1929 - ), The Order of Ikhamanga in Silver\"], The Presidency, Republic of South Africa.</ref><ref>Aziz Matthews,[https://seekingthesoapbox.wordpress.com/2014/05/15/james-matthews-struggle-poet-and-laureate-of-national-honours/ \"James Matthews: Struggle poet and laureate of National Honours\"], Seeking the Soapbox, 15 May 2014.</ref>\n\nOn 11 March 2013 he received an honorary doctorate from the [[University of the Western Cape]].<ref>[https://www.uwc.ac.za/Pages/2013-March-Graduation.aspx \"UWC honours struggle poet and sports administrator at its Summer Graduation\"], 2013 March Graduation, University of the Western Cape.</ref> [[Rhodes University]] in [[Grahamstown]] also awarded him an honorary doctorate, on 31 March 2016.<ref>[https://www.ru.ac.za/latestnews/acatwhogotluckywithwords.html \"A Cat Who Got Lucky With Words\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806074305/https://www.ru.ac.za/latestnews/acatwhogotluckywithwords.html |date=6 August 2016 }}, Rhodes University, 31 March 2016.</ref><ref>Yazeed Kamaldien, [https://www.ru.ac.za/studentlife/rhodesnews/articles/capepoeturgesuniversitiestoteachhiswork.html \"Cape poet urges universities to teach his work\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806113803/https://www.ru.ac.za/studentlife/rhodesnews/articles/capepoeturgesuniversitiestoteachhiswork.html |date=6 August 2016 }}, ''Studentlife'', Rhodes University, 30 March 2016.</ref>\n\n===Film===\nIn 2014, Shelley Barry's documentary ''Diaries of A Dissident Poet'', a film profiling James Matthews,<ref>Rustum Kozain, [http://africasacountry.com/2014/07/james-matthews-being-james-matthews/ \"James Matthews being James Matthews\"], Africa is a Country, 31 July 2014.</ref> premiered at the Encounters Film Festival in South Africa.<ref>http://www.encounters.co.za/</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* Woza Afrika Award (1978)\n* Kwaza Honours List \u2014 Black Arts Celebration, Chicago, U.S.A. (1979)\n* Freeman of Lehrte and Nienburg, Germany (1982)\n* National Order of Ikhamanga, South African government (2004)\n* Honorary doctorate, University of the Western Cape (2013)\n* Honorary doctorate, Rhodes University (2016)\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Poetry===\n*''Cry Rage'' (1972), Spro-Cas Publications\n*''Black Voices Shout'' (1974)\n*''Pass me a Meatball, Jones'' (1977)\n*''No Time for Dreams'' (1981), BLAC Publications\n*''Poisoned Wells and Other Delights'' (1990), BLAC Publications\n*''Flames and Flowers'' (2000), Realities\n*''Poems from a Prison Cell'' (2002), Realities\n*''Age is a Beautiful Phase'' (2008), Realities\n*''Gently Stirs My Soul'' (2015), Rhodes University\n\n===Short stories===\n*''The Park and Other Stories'' (1983), Ravan Press\n\n===Novels===\n*''The Party is Over'' (1997), Kwela\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ukzn.ac.za/cca/PoetryAfrica2002bios15.html#JAMES%20MATTHEWS Poetry Africa UKZN entry]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110604093719/http://www.info.gov.za/aboutgovt/orders/2004/matthews.htm SA Government page]\n* Mphutlane Wa Bofelo, [http://botsotso.org.za/2013/05/james-matthews-still-kicking-butt-77/ \"James Matthews: Still Kicking Butt @ 77\"], ''Botsotso'', 6 May 2013.\n* James Matthews, [http://mg.co.za/article/2016-04-13-how-reading-can-change-your-life \"How reading can change your life\"], ''Mail & Guardian'', 15 April 2016.\n*  Paul Maylam, [https://www.ru.ac.za/media/rhodesuniversity/content/alumni/documents/CITATION%20FOR%20JAMES%20MATTHEWS%20(2).pdf \"Citation for James Matthews\"] (Honorary graduand, Rhodes University, 31 March 2016).\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Matthews, James}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Ikhamanga]]\n[[Category:Anti-apartheid activists]]\n[[Category:International Writing Program alumni]]\n[[Category:South African publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:South African journalists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Cape Town]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Matthews_(writer)"}
{"title_page": "K. Gopalaiah", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = K. Gopalaiah\n| honorific_prefix = \n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = \n| birth_place      = \n| residence        = \n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n\n| office     = Minister of Food, Civil supplies and Consumer affairs<br/> [[Government of Karnataka]]\n| term_start = 06 February 2020\n| term_end   = \n| 1blankname = Chief Minister\n| 1namedata  = [[B. S. Yediyurappa]]\n|predecessor = [[Shashikala Annasaheb Jolle]]\n\n\n\n| office3        = [[Member of Legislative Assembly (India)|Member of the Karnataka Legislative Assembly]]\n| term_start3    = 13 May 2013\n| term_end3      = \n| constituency3  = [[Mahalakshmi Layout (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Mahalakshmi Layout]]\n| predecessor3   = N. L. Narendra Babu\n| successor3     = \n| chiefminister3 = \n\n| party       = [[Bharatiya Janata party]] <br />{{small|(2019\u2013present)}}\n| otherparty  = [[Janata Dal (Secular)]]<br />{{small|(till 2019)}}\n| spouse      = \n| children    = \n| website     = \n| footnotes   = \n| year        = \n| education   = \n| nationality = Indian\n}}\n\n'''K. Gopalaiah''' is an Indian politician. He was elected to the [[Karnataka Legislative Assembly]] from [[Mahalakshmi Layout (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Mahalakshmi Layout]] in the [[2018 Karnataka Legislative Assembly election]] as a member of [[Janata Dal (Secular)]].<ref>[http://myneta.info/karnataka2018/candidate.php?candidate_id=6410 MyNeta]</ref><ref>[https://www.oneindia.com/india/karnataka-election-results-2018-full-list-of-winners-bjp-congress-jds-2696524.html Karnataka MLA's List 2018: Full List of Winners From BJP, Congress, JDS and More]</ref><ref>[https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/disqualified-karnataka-mlas-barring-roshan-baig-join-bjp/articleshow/72051891.cms Disqualified Karnataka MLAs, barring Roshan Baig, join BJP]</ref><ref>[https://www.freepressjournal.in/india/rebel-karnataka-mlas-barring-roshan-baig-to-join-bjp-after-sc-allows-them-to-contest-bypolls Rebel Karnataka MLAs barring Roshan Baig to join BJP after SC allows them to contest bypolls]</ref>, but later joined the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] in 2019 and won the by-elections the same year.\n\n==Controversies==\n===Operation Kamala===\n{{Main|Operation Kamala|Operation Kamala in Karnataka}}\n{{#section:Operation Kamala|lead section}}\n\nHe was one of the 15 MLAs fell for Operation Kamala and resigned in July 2019, effectively bringing down the [[H. D. Kumaraswamy]]-led coalition government of [[Indian National Congress]] and [[Janata Dal (Secular)]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/galleries/nation/2019/jul/24/the-15-mlas-who-brought-down-kumaraswamy-government-102416.html|title=The 15 MLAs who brought down Kumaraswamy government|newspaper=[[The New Indian Express]]|accessdate=28 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n{{reflist}}\n{{Bharatiya Janata Party}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gopalaiah, K.}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Karnataka Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Janata Dal (Secular) politicians]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:People from Bangalore]]\n[[Category:Karnataka MLAs 2018\u2013]]\n\n\n{{India-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = K. Gopalaiah\n| honorific_prefix = \n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = \n| birth_place      = \n| residence        = \n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n\n| office     = Minister of Food, Civil supplies and Consumer affairs<br/> [[Government of Karnataka]]\n| term_start = 06 February 2020\n| term_en