was one of the 15 MLAs fell for Operation Kamala and resigned in July 2019, effectively bringing down the [[H. D. Kumaraswamy]]-led coalition government of [[Indian National Congress]] and [[Janata Dal (Secular)]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/galleries/nation/2019/jul/24/the-15-mlas-who-brought-down-kumaraswamy-government-102416.html|title=The 15 MLAs who brought down Kumaraswamy government|newspaper=[[The New Indian Express]]|accessdate=28 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n{{reflist}}\n{{Bharatiya Janata Party}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gopalaiah, K.}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Karnataka Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Janata Dal (Secular) politicians]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:People from Bangalore]]\n[[Category:Karnataka MLAs 2018\u2013]]\n\n\n{{India-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jarbell", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K._Gopalaiah"}
{"title_page": "Generalization (learning)", "text_new": "'''Generalization''' is the concept that humans and animals use past learning in present situations of learning if the conditions in the situations are regarded as similar.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gluck|first1=Mark A.|last2=Mercado|first2=Eduardo|last3=Myers|first3=Catherine E.|title=Learning and memory : from brain to behavior|date=2011|publisher=Worth Publishers|location=New York|isbn=9781429240147|page=209|edition=2nd}}</ref> The learner uses generalized patterns, principles, and other similarities between past experiences and novel experiences to more efficiently navigate the world.<ref>Banich, M. T., Dukes, P., & Caccamise, D. (2010). Generalization of knowledge: Multidisciplinary perspectives. Psychology Press.</ref> For example, if a person has learned in the past that every time they eat an apple, their throat becomes itchy and swollen, they might assume they are allergic to all fruit. When this person is offered a banana to eat, they reject it upon assuming they are also allergic to it through generalizing that all fruits cause the same reaction. Although this generalization about being allergic to all fruit based on experiences with one fruit could be correct in some cases, it may not be correct in all. Both positive and negative effects have been shown in education through learned generalization and its contrasting notion of [[discrimination learning]].\n\n== '''Overview''' ==\nGeneralization is understood to be directly tied to the [[Transfer of learning|transfer]] of [[knowledge]] across multiple situations.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Walker|first1=J. E.|last2=Shea|first2=T. M.|last3=Bauer|first3=A.M.|title=Generalization and the Effects of Consequences {{!}} Education.com|url=http://www.education.com/reference/article/generalization-effects-consequences/|website=www.education.com|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> Generalization allows humans and animals to recognize the similarities in knowledge acquired in one circumstance, allowing for transfer of knowledge onto new situations. This idea rivals the theory of [[situated cognition]], instead stating that one can apply past knowledge to learning in new situations and environments.\n\nGeneralization is shown to have implications on the use of the [[spacing effect]] in educational settings.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Vlach|first1=Haley A.|title=The Spacing Effect in Children's Generalization of Knowledge: Allowing Children Time to Forget Promotes Their Ability to Learn|journal=Child Development Perspectives|date=September 2014|volume=8|issue=3|pages=163\u2013168|doi=10.1111/cdep.12079}}</ref> In the past, it was thought that the information forgotten between periods of learning when implementing [[spaced presentation]] inhibited generalization. In more recent years, this forgetting has been seen as promoting generalization through repetition of information during each occasion of spaced learning. The effects of gaining [[Long-term memory|long-term]] generalization knowledge through spaced learning can be compared with that of massed learning (lengthy and all at once; for example, cramming the night before an exam)<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gluck|first1=Mark A.|last2=Mercado|first2=Eduardo|last3=Myers|first3=Catherine E.|title=Learning and memory : from brain to behavior|date=2014|publisher=Worth Publishers|location=New York|isbn=9781429240147|page=312|edition=2nd}}</ref> in which a person only gains [[Short-term memory|short-term]] knowledge, decreasing the likelihood of establishing generalization.\n\nA specific type of generalization, fear generalization, occurs when a person associates fears learned in the past through [[classical conditioning]] to similar situations, events, people, and objects in their present. When fear generalization becomes [[Maladaptation|maladaptive]] it is connected to many [[anxiety disorder]]s.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dymond|first1=Simon|last2=Dunsmoor|first2=Joseph E.|last3=Vervliet|first3=Bram|last4=Roche|first4=Bryan|last5=Hermans|first5=Dirk|title=Fear Generalization in Humans: Systematic Review and Implications for Anxiety Disorder Research|journal=Behavior Therapy|date=September 2015|volume=46|issue=5|pages=561\u2013582|doi=10.1016/j.beth.2014.10.001}}</ref> This maladaptation is often referred to as the overgeneralization of fear and can also lead to the development of [[posttraumatic stress disorder]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Besnard|first1=Antoine|last2=Sahay|first2=Amar|title=Adult Hippocampal Neurogenesis, Fear Generalization, and Stress|journal=Neuropsychopharmacology|date=12 June 2015|volume=41|issue=1|pages=24\u201344|doi=10.1038/npp.2015.167|pmid=26068726|pmc=4677119}}</ref>\n\nGeneralization has been shown to be refined and/or stabilized after sleep.<ref>{{cite journal|pmid=14534586|year=2003|last1=Fenn|first1=KM|last2=Nusbaum|first2=HC|last3=Margoliash|first3=D|title=Consolidation during sleep of perceptual learning of spoken language|volume=425|issue=6958|pages=614\u20136|doi=10.1038/nature01951|journal=Nature}}</ref>\n\nIn scientific studies looking at generalization, a generalization gradient is often used. This tool is used to measure how often and how much animals or humans respond to certain stimuli, depending on whether the stimuli are similar or different. For example, when measuring responses to color, it is expected that subjects will respond to colors similar to each other, like shades of pink after being exposed to red, as opposed to a non-similar shade of blue.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gluck|first1=Mark A.|last2=Mercado|first2=Eduardo|last3=Myers|first3=Catherine E.|title=Learning and memory : from brain to behavior|date=2014|publisher=Worth Publishers|location=New York|isbn=9781429240147|page=212|edition=2nd}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Learning theory (education)]]\n", "text_old": "'''Generalization''' is the concept that humans and animals use past learning in present situations of learning if the conditions in the situations are regarded as similar.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gluck|first1=Mark A.|last2=Mercado|first2=Eduardo|last3=Myers|first3=Catherine E.|title=Learning and memory : from brain to behavior|date=2011|publisher=Worth Publishers|location=New York|isbn=9781429240147|page=209|edition=2nd}}</ref> The learner uses generalized patterns, principles, and other similarities between past experiences and novel experiences to more efficiently navigate the world.<ref>Banich, M. T., Dukes, P., & Caccamise, D. (2010). Generalization of knowledge: Multidisciplinary perspectives. Psychology Press.</ref> For example, if a person has learned in the past that every time they eat an apple, their throat becomes itchy and swollen, they might assume they are allergic to all fruit. When this person is offered a banana to eat, they reject it upon assuming they are also allergic to it through generalizing that all fruits cause the same reaction. Although this generalization about being allergic to all fruit based on experiences with one fruit could be correct in some cases, it may not be correct in all. Both positive and negative effects have been shown in education through learned generalization and its contrasting notion of [[discrimination learning]].\n\nGeneralization is understood to be directly tied to the [[Transfer of learning|transfer]] of [[knowledge]] across multiple situations.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Walker|first1=J. E.|last2=Shea|first2=T. M.|last3=Bauer|first3=A.M.|title=Generalization and the Effects of Consequences {{!}} Education.com|url=http://www.education.com/reference/article/generalization-effects-consequences/|website=www.education.com|accessdate=5 May 2016}}</ref> Generalization allows humans and animals to recognize the similarities in knowledge acquired in one circumstance, allowing for transfer of knowledge onto new situations. This idea rivals the theory of [[situated cognition]], instead stating that one can apply past knowledge to learning in new situations and environments.\n\nGeneralization is shown to have implications on the use of the [[spacing effect]] in educational settings.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Vlach|first1=Haley A.|title=The Spacing Effect in Children's Generalization of Knowledge: Allowing Children Time to Forget Promotes Their Ability to Learn|journal=Child Development Perspectives|date=September 2014|volume=8|issue=3|pages=163\u2013168|doi=10.1111/cdep.12079}}</ref> In the past, it was thought that the information forgotten between periods of learning when implementing [[spaced presentation]] inhibited generalization. In more recent years, this forgetting has been seen as promoting generalization through repetition of information during each occasion of spaced learning. The effects of gaining [[Long-term memory|long-term]] generalization knowledge through spaced learning can be compared with that of massed learning (lengthy and all at once; for example, cramming the night before an exam)<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gluck|first1=Mark A.|last2=Mercado|first2=Eduardo|last3=Myers|first3=Catherine E.|title=Learning and memory : from brain to behavior|date=2014|publisher=Worth Publishers|location=New York|isbn=9781429240147|page=312|edition=2nd}}</ref> in which a person only gains [[Short-term memory|short-term]] knowledge, decreasing the likelihood of establishing generalization.\n\nA specific type of generalization, fear generalization, occurs when a person associates fears learned in the past through [[classical conditioning]] to similar situations, events, people, and objects in their present. When fear generalization becomes [[Maladaptation|maladaptive]] it is connected to many [[anxiety disorder]]s.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Dymond|first1=Simon|last2=Dunsmoor|first2=Joseph E.|last3=Vervliet|first3=Bram|last4=Roche|first4=Bryan|last5=Hermans|first5=Dirk|title=Fear Generalization in Humans: Systematic Review and Implications for Anxiety Disorder Research|journal=Behavior Therapy|date=September 2015|volume=46|issue=5|pages=561\u2013582|doi=10.1016/j.beth.2014.10.001}}</ref> This maladaptation is often referred to as the overgeneralization of fear and can also lead to the development of [[posttraumatic stress disorder]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Besnard|first1=Antoine|last2=Sahay|first2=Amar|title=Adult Hippocampal Neurogenesis, Fear Generalization, and Stress|journal=Neuropsychopharmacology|date=12 June 2015|volume=41|issue=1|pages=24\u201344|doi=10.1038/npp.2015.167|pmid=26068726|pmc=4677119}}</ref>\n\nGeneralization has been shown to be refined and/or stabilized after sleep.<ref>{{cite journal|pmid=14534586|year=2003|last1=Fenn|first1=KM|last2=Nusbaum|first2=HC|last3=Margoliash|first3=D|title=Consolidation during sleep of perceptual learning of spoken language|volume=425|issue=6958|pages=614\u20136|doi=10.1038/nature01951|journal=Nature}}</ref>\n\nIn scientific studies looking at generalization, a generalization gradient is often used. This tool is used to measure how often and how much animals or humans respond to certain stimuli, depending on whether the stimuli are similar or different. For example, when measuring responses to color, it is expected that subjects will respond to colors similar to each other, like shades of pink after being exposed to red, as opposed to a non-similar shade of blue.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gluck|first1=Mark A.|last2=Mercado|first2=Eduardo|last3=Myers|first3=Catherine E.|title=Learning and memory : from brain to behavior|date=2014|publisher=Worth Publishers|location=New York|isbn=9781429240147|page=212|edition=2nd}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Learning theory (education)]]\n", "name_user": "Kwhit24", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added a subsection header.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generalization_(learning)"}
{"title_page": "Chris Mann (poet)", "text_new": "'''Christopher Michael Zithulele Mann'''{{Sfn|Eve|2003|pp=135-136}} (born 1948 in [[Port Elizabeth]], [[South Africa]]) is a South African poet.{{Sfn|Eve|2003|pp=135-136}}\n\n== Biography ==\n\nChris Mann was born in [[Port Elizabeth]] in 1948 and went to school in [[Cape Town]].  He studied English and Philosophy at the [[University of the Witwatersrand]], and went to [[Oxford University]] as a [[Rhodes Scholar]] where he was awarded an MA in English Language and Literature. He also studied African Oral Literature at the [[School of Oriental and African Languages]] in [[London]].<ref name=Jobson>{{cite web|last1=Jobson|first1=Liesl|title=Chris Mann|url=http://www.poetryinternationalweb.net/pi/site/poet/item/12582/10/Chris-Mann|website=Poetry International Rotterdam|publisher=Poetry International|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref> From 1977 to 1980 he held a lecturer post in the English Department at Rhodes University in [[Grahamstown]], [[South Africa]].  From 1980 to 1995 he worked with an NGO, The [[Valley Trust]]<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|author=Anon|title=Annual Report of the Valley Trust|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7A4zAQAAIAAJ|year=1989|publisher=Valley Trust.}}</ref> after which he returned to [[Rhodes University]] where he is presently a professor of poetry with the Institute for the Study of English in Africa.{{Sfn|Eve|2003|p=135}} He is founder and convenor of Wordfest, a national multilingual festival of South African languages and literature with a developmental emphasis.<ref name=Jobson /><ref>{{cite web|title=Wordfest- Rhodes University|url=http://www.ru.ac.za/wordfest/|website=Rhodes University|publisher=Rhodes University|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref>{{Sfn|Eve|2003|p=136}} A native English speaker, Mann is also conversant in Afrikaans, isiZulu and isiXhosa. He performs his work at festivals, schools, churches, universities and conferences in South Africa.<ref name=Jobson /> He is married to artist Julia Skeen.{{Sfn|Eve|2003|p=135}}\n\n== Works ==\n\n=== Books ===\n\n* ''First Poems'', 1979. Cape Town: Bateleur Press.\n* ''A New Book of South African Verse'', 1979. With [[Guy Butler (poet)|Guy Butler]]. Cape Town: OUP.\n* {{cite book|first=Chris|last=Mann|title=New Shades|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nMsvAAAAIAAJ|year=1982|publisher=David Philip|isbn=978-0-908396-54-2|display-authors=0}}\n* {{cite book|first=Chris|last=Mann|title=Kites, and Other Poems|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TLE-PKnNFo8C|year=1990|publisher=New Africa Books|isbn=978-0-86486-151-1|display-authors=0}}\n* {{cite book|first=Chris|last=Mann|title=Mann Alive!: Poems|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-l2lwCvKgCcC|year=1992|publisher=David Philip|isbn=978-0-86486-239-6|display-authors=0}}\n* {{cite book|first=Chris|last=Mann|title=South Africans: a set of portrait-poems|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HuDyAAAAMAAJ|year=1996|publisher=University of Natal Press|isbn=978-0-86980-922-8|display-authors=0}}\n* {{cite book|author1=Chris Mann|author2=Julia Skeen|title=The horn of plenty: a series of painting-poems|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R93yAAAAMAAJ|year=1997|publisher=ISEA, Rhodes University|isbn=978-0-86810-324-2|display-authors=0}} with Julia Skeen\n* ''The Roman Centurion\u2019s Good Friday'', 1999. Grahamstown: [[St Michael and St George Cathedral, Grahamstown|Cathedral of St Michael & St George]].\n* {{cite book|first=Chris|last=Mann|title=Heartlands|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OhlbAAAAMAAJ|date=2002|publisher=University of Natal Press|isbn=978-1-86914-010-6|display-authors=0}}\n* ''In Praise of the Shades'', 2003. Grahamstown: [[St Michael and St George Cathedral, Grahamstown|Cathedral of St Michael and St George]].\n* ''Walking on Gravity'', 2004. Grahamstown: [[St Michael and St George Cathedral, Grahamstown|Cathedral of St Michael and St George]].\n* ''Thuthula'', 2005. Johannesburg: Ravan & PanMacmillan.\n* ''Beautiful Lofty Things'', 2005. Grahamstown: [[St Michael and St George Cathedral, Grahamstown|Cathedral of St Michael and St George]].\n* ''Walking on Gravity'', 2005. In: Dante in South Africa. Cullinan, Patrick and Watson, Stephen (Eds.). Cape Town: Centre for Creative Writing, University of Cape Town.\n* ''Lifelines'', 2006. With: Skeen, Julia and Craig, Adrian. Pietermaritzburg: UKZN Press.\n* {{cite book|author1=Chris Mann|author2=Julia Skeen|title=Home from Home: New and Selected Poems|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UbpbYgEACAAJ|year=2010|publisher=Echoing Green Press|isbn=978-0-9802501-7-6|display-authors=0}} with Julia Skeen\n* ''Small Town Big Voice'', 2012. Ed. Renard, Andrew. Port Elizabeth: SACEE.\n* ''Rudiments of Grace'', 2014. Grahamstown: [[St Michael and St George Cathedral, Grahamstown|Cathedral of St Michael and St George]].{{Sfn|Greybe|2014}}\n* ''Epiphanies .' 2017. Grahamstown. [[St Michael and St George Cathedral, Grahamstown|Cathedral of St Michael and St George]].\n* ' 'Heraclitus in Africa. forthcoming.\n\n{{Sfn|Greybe|2014}}\n\n=== Plays in verse and multimedia poetry productions ===\n\n* ''The Sand Labyrinth''. 1980 National Student Drama Festival.\n* ''Mahoon\u2019s Testimony''. Broadcast on SAfm in 1998, rebroadcast 2007.\n* ''Frail Care''. Broadcast on SAfm in 1997 and re-broadcast in 1999 and 2007.\n* ''The Crux of Being''. 1999 National Arts Festival Fringe.\n* ''In Praise of the Shades''. 2003 National Arts Festival Fringe.\n* ''Thuthula''. 2003 National Arts Festival Main Programme.\n* ''Walking on Gravity''. 2004 National Arts Festival Fringe.\n* ''Beautiful Lofty Things''. 2005 National Arts Festival Fringe production.\n* ''Lifelines''. 2006 National Arts Festival Fringe poetry performance production.\n* ''LifeSongs''. 2007 National Arts Festival Fringe installation.\n* ''Epiphanies''. 2008. National Arts Festival Fringe installation.\n* ''LifeSongs''. 2011. National English Literary Museum installation.\n* ''The Ballad of Dirk de Bruin'', 2014.{{Sfn|Cue Online|2014}}{{Sfn|Mail and Guardian|2014-06-13}} National Arts Festival Fringe.\n* Anxiety and Grace. With Julia Skeen. 2016. National Arts Festival Fringe and Spiritfest.\n*Epiphanies. With Julia Skeen. 2018. National Arts Festival Fringe and Spiritfest.\n\n===Articles===\n* {{cite journal|last1=Mann|first1=Chris|title=The Guttural Muse in the Sky: A valediction for Seamus Heaney|journal=English Academy Review|volume=30|issue=2|year=2013|pages=129\u2013132|issn=1013-1752|doi=10.1080/10131752.2013.843906|display-authors=0}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Mann|first1=Chris|title=Saturnalia satirica: six satires wearing masks|journal=Scrutiny2|volume=19|issue=1|year=2014|pages=147\u2013151|issn=1812-5441|doi=10.1080/18125441.2014.906257|display-authors=0}}\n*\"Creation and translation.\" Ileana Dimitriu & Chris Mann. Current Writing, Volume 19, 2007 - Issue 1 <ref>{{Cite journal|doi=10.1080/1013929x.2007.9678260|title = Creation and translation|journal = Current Writing|volume = 19|pages = 21\u201352|year = 2007|last1 = Dimitriu|first1 = Ileana|last2 = Mann|first2 = Chris}}</ref>\n*\"Seeing the cosmos in a grain of sand.\" Chris Mann. Current Writing, Volume 20, 2008 - Issue 2 <ref>{{Cite journal|doi=10.1080/1013929x.2008.9678304|title = Seeing the cosmos in a grain of sand|journal = Current Writing|volume = 20|issue = 2|pages = 108\u2013126|year = 2008|last1 = Mann|first1 = Chris}}</ref>\n*\"The Poetry of Belonging. Episodic Memory and Italian and South African Shades.\" English Literature | 3 | 2016 <ref>{{Cite journal|title=The Poetry of Belonging|journal=English Literature|url=http://edizionicafoscari.unive.it/riviste/english-literature/2016/1numero-monografico/the-poetry-of-belonging/|language=en|doi=10.14277/2420-823x/el-3-16-1|last1=Mann|first1=Chris|year=2016}}</ref>\n*\"Points of Illumination: Wordfest South Africa This Year and Next.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pensouthafrica.co.za/points-of-illumination-wordfest-south-africa-this-year-and-next/|title=Points of Illumination: Wordfest South Africa This Year and Next {{!}} PEN South Africa|last=LindsayC|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>\n\n== Commentary on Mann's Work ==\n\nMann's work has received critical consideration in journals such as\n* ''The English Academy Review'';{{Sfn|Brown|2011|pp=64\u201372}}{{Sfn|Brown|2007|pp=134\u2013137}}{{Sfn|Johnson|1996|pp=75\u2013102}}{{Sfn|Gardner|1995|pp=99\u2013107}}{{Sfn|Foley|1991|pp=15\u201329}}{{Sfn|Butler|1985|pp=163\u2013176}}\n* ''English in Africa'';{{Sfn|Mehuizen|2007|pp=133\u2013140}}\n* ''Shakespeare in Southern Africa'';{{Sfn|Gagiano|2009|pp=95\u201398}}\n* ''Scrutiny2'';{{Sfn|Levey|2010|pp=55\u201369}} and\n* ''Literator''.\n\n== Awards ==\n\n* Newdigate Prize for Poetry while a Rhodes Scholar at Oxford. \n* Olive Schreiner Prize for South African Poetry in English. \n* South African Performing Arts Councils\u2019 Playwright Award. \n* Hon.D.Litt. University of Durban-Westville, now University of KwaZulu-Natal.\n* Eastern Cape Premier\u2019s Award for Literature. \n* First Professor of Poetry, Rhodes University.\n* English Academy of South Africa Thomas Pringle Award for Poetry. \n* Mann's 2014 play ''The Ballad of Dirk de Bruin'' which premiered at the [[National Arts Festival]] was awarded a Silver [[Standard Bank]] Ovation Award for \"artistic innovation, excellence and the exploration of new performance styles\".{{Sfn|Cue|6 July 2014|p=19}}{{Sfn|Grocotts|2014}}\n* Honorary Artist in Residence, Grahamstown Cathedral (2017\u2013present)\n*Guest poet, Incroci di civilt\u00e0 international poetry festival, Venice 2019\n*English Academy of South Africa Gold Medal 2019\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n\n* {{cite book|last=Eve|first=Jeanette |title=A Literary Guide to the Eastern Cape: Places and the Voices of Writers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uwFXGL059QgC&pg=PA136|accessdate=16 September 2013|year=2003|publisher=Juta and Company Ltd|isbn=978-1-919930-15-2|ref= harv}}\n* {{Cite journal\n| last1=Butler\n| first1=G.\n| year=1985\n| title=English and the English in the New South Africa\n| journal=English Academy Review\n| volume=3\n| issue=1\n| pages=163\u2013176\n| doi=10.1080/10131758585310141\n| ref=harv\n }}\n* {{Cite journal\n| last1=Foley\n| first1=A.\n| year=1991\n| title=The white English-speaking South Africans: 'Bastards', 'Wimps', 'Ghosts with ears', or something else again?\n| journal=English Academy Review\n| volume=8\n| issue=1\n| pages=15\u201329\n| doi=10.1080/10131759185310041\n| ref=harv\n }}\n* {{Cite journal\n| last1=Johnson\n| first1=A.\n| year=1996\n| title='The president waves back': Twelve recent books of poetry\n| journal=English Academy Review\n| volume=13\n| issue=1\n| pages=75\u2013102\n| doi=10.1080/10131759685310091\n| ref=harv\n }}\n* {{Cite journal\n| last1=Gardner\n| first1=C.\n| year=1995\n| title=A rediscovery of the ordinary: A reading of three recent poems by Chris Mann\n| journal=English Academy Review\n| volume=12\n| issue=1\n| pages=99\u2013107\n| doi=10.1080/10131759585310111\n| ref=harv\n }}\n* {{Cite journal\n| last1=Meihuizen\n| first1=N.\n| year=2007\n| title=Lifelines, Chris Mann, Adrian Craig, and Julia Skeen : book review\n| journal=English in Africa\n| volume=34\n| issue=2\n| pages=133\u2013140\n| issn=0376-8902\n| url=http://reference.sabinet.co.za/sa_epublication_article/iseaeng_v34_n2_a10\n| ref=harv\n }}\n* {{Cite journal\n| last1=Brown\n| first1=M.\n| year=2007\n| title=The fixative of earth and mind \u2026\n| journal=English Academy Review\n| volume=24\n| issue=1\n| pages=134\u2013137\n| doi=10.1080/17535360712331393530\n| ref=harv\n }}\n* {{Cite journal\n| last1=Gagiano\n| first1=A.\n| year=2009\n| title=Thuthula : Heart of the Labyrinth, Chris Zithulele Mann : book review\n| journal=Shakespeare in Southern Africa\n| volume=21\n| pages=95\u201398\n| issn=1011-582X\n| url=http://reference.sabinet.co.za/sa_epublication_article/iseasosa_v21_a16\n| ref=harv\n| doi=