{Official website| http://www.chrismann.co.za/ }}\n* [http://www.literarytourism.co.za/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=370:chris-mann&catid=13:authors&Itemid=28 Biography, KZN Literary Tourism]\n* [http://www.poetryinternationalweb.net/pi/site/poet/item/12582/10/Chris-Mann Biography, Poetry International Rotterdam]\n* [http://mg.co.za/author/chris-mann Articles, Mail and Guardian]\n* [http://www.englishexperience.co.za/chris-mann.htm Interview, English Experience]\n\n{{African topic || literature}}\n{{South Africa topics}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mann, Chris}}\n[[Category:20th-century South African poets]]\n[[Category:English-language poets]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St Edmund Hall, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of London]]\n[[Category:Rhodes University academics]]\n[[Category:People from Port Elizabeth]]\n[[Category:South African Rhodes Scholars]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African poets]]\n[[Category:South African male poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African male writers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Christopher Michael Zithulele Mann'''{{Sfn|Eve|2003|pp=135-136}} (born 1948 in [[Port Elizabeth]], [[South Africa]]) is a South African poet.{{Sfn|Eve|2003|pp=135-136}}\n\n== Biography ==\n\nChris Mann was born in [[Port Elizabeth]] in 1948 and went to school in [[Cape Town]].  He studied English and Philosophy at the [[University of the Witwatersrand]], and went to [[Oxford University]] as a [[Rhodes Scholar]] where he was awarded an MA in English Language and Literature. He also studied African Oral Literature at the [[School of Oriental and African Languages]] in [[London]].<ref name=Jobson>{{cite web|last1=Jobson|first1=Liesl|title=Chris Mann|url=http://www.poetryinternationalweb.net/pi/site/poet/item/12582/10/Chris-Mann|website=Poetry International Rotterdam|publisher=Poetry International|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref> From 1977 to 1980 he held a lecturer post in the English Department at Rhodes University in [[Grahamstown]], [[South Africa]].  From 1980 to 1995 he worked with an NGO, The [[Valley Trust]]<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|author=Anon|title=Annual Report of the Valley Trust|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7A4zAQAAIAAJ|year=1989|publisher=Valley Trust.}}</ref> after which he returned to [[Rhodes University]] where he is presently a professor of poetry with the Institute for the Study of English in Africa.{{Sfn|Eve|2003|p=135}} He is founder and convenor of Wordfest, a national multilingual festival of South African languages and literature with a developmental emphasis.<ref name=Jobson /><ref>{{cite web|title=Wordfest- Rhodes University|url=http://www.ru.ac.za/wordfest/|website=Rhodes University|publisher=Rhodes University|accessdate=13 February 2015}}</ref>{{Sfn|Eve|2003|p=136}} A native English speaker, Mann is also conversant in Afrikaans, isiZulu and isiXhosa. He performs his work at festivals, schools, churches, universities and conferences in South Africa.<ref name=Jobson /> He is married to artist Julia Skeen.{{Sfn|Eve|2003|p=135}}\n\n== Works ==\n\n=== Books ===\n\n* ''First Poems'', 1979. Cape Town: Bateleur Press.\n* ''A New Book of South African Verse'', 1979. With [[Guy Butler (poet)|Guy Butler]]. Cape Town: OUP.\n* {{cite book|first=Chris|last=Mann|title=New Shades|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nMsvAAAAIAAJ|year=1982|publisher=David Philip|isbn=978-0-908396-54-2|display-authors=0}}\n* {{cite book|first=Chris|last=Mann|title=Kites, and Other Poems|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TLE-PKnNFo8C|year=1990|publisher=New Africa Books|isbn=978-0-86486-151-1|display-authors=0}}\n* {{cite book|first=Chris|last=Mann|title=Mann Alive!: Poems|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-l2lwCvKgCcC|year=1992|publisher=David Philip|isbn=978-0-86486-239-6|display-authors=0}}\n* {{cite book|first=Chris|last=Mann|title=South Africans: a set of portrait-poems|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HuDyAAAAMAAJ|year=1996|publisher=University of Natal Press|isbn=978-0-86980-922-8|display-authors=0}}\n* {{cite book|author1=Chris Mann|author2=Julia Skeen|title=The horn of plenty: a series of painting-poems|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R93yAAAAMAAJ|year=1997|publisher=ISEA, Rhodes University|isbn=978-0-86810-324-2|display-authors=0}} with Julia Skeen\n* ''The Roman Centurion\u2019s Good Friday'', 1999. Grahamstown: [[St Michael and St George Cathedral, Grahamstown|Cathedral of St Michael & St George]].\n* {{cite book|first=Chris|last=Mann|title=Heartlands|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OhlbAAAAMAAJ|date=2002|publisher=University of Natal Press|isbn=978-1-86914-010-6|display-authors=0}}\n* ''In Praise of the Shades'', 2003. Grahamstown: [[St Michael and St George Cathedral, Grahamstown|Cathedral of St Michael and St George]].\n* ''Walking on Gravity'', 2004. Grahamstown: [[St Michael and St George Cathedral, Grahamstown|Cathedral of St Michael and St George]].\n* ''Thuthula'', 2005. Johannesburg: Ravan & PanMacmillan.\n* ''Beautiful Lofty Things'', 2005. Grahamstown: [[St Michael and St George Cathedral, Grahamstown|Cathedral of St Michael and St George]].\n* ''Walking on Gravity'', 2005. In: Dante in South Africa. Cullinan, Patrick and Watson, Stephen (Eds.). Cape Town: Centre for Creative Writing, University of Cape Town.\n* ''Lifelines'', 2006. With: Skeen, Julia and Craig, Adrian. Pietermaritzburg: UKZN Press.\n* {{cite book|author1=Chris Mann|author2=Julia Skeen|title=Home from Home: New and Selected Poems|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UbpbYgEACAAJ|year=2010|publisher=Echoing Green Press|isbn=978-0-9802501-7-6|display-authors=0}} with Julia Skeen\n* ''Small Town Big Voice'', 2012. Ed. Renard, Andrew. Port Elizabeth: SACEE.\n* ''Rudiments of Grace'', 2014. Grahamstown: [[St Michael and St George Cathedral, Grahamstown|Cathedral of St Michael and St George]].{{Sfn|Greybe|2014}}\n* ''Epiphanies .' 2017. Grahamstown. [[St Michael and St George Cathedral, Grahamstown|Cathedral of St Michael and St George]].\n* ' 'Heraclitus in Africa. forthcoming.\n\n{{Sfn|Greybe|2014}}\n\n=== Plays in verse and multimedia poetry productions ===\n\n* ''The Sand Labyrinth''. 1980 National Student Drama Festival.\n* ''Mahoon\u2019s Testimony''. Broadcast on SAfm in 1998, rebroadcast 2007.\n* ''Frail Care''. Broadcast on SAfm in 1997 and re-broadcast in 1999 and 2007.\n* ''The Crux of Being''. 1999 National Arts Festival Fringe.\n* ''In Praise of the Shades''. 2003 National Arts Festival Fringe.\n* ''Thuthula''. 2003 National Arts Festival Main Programme.\n* ''Walking on Gravity''. 2004 National Arts Festival Fringe.\n* ''Beautiful Lofty Things''. 2005 National Arts Festival Fringe production.\n* ''Lifelines''. 2006 National Arts Festival Fringe poetry performance production.\n* ''LifeSongs''. 2007 National Arts Festival Fringe installation.\n* ''Epiphanies''. 2008. National Arts Festival Fringe installation.\n* ''LifeSongs''. 2011. National English Literary Museum installation.\n* ''The Ballad of Dirk de Bruin'', 2014.{{Sfn|Cue Online|2014}}{{Sfn|Mail and Guardian|2014-06-13}} National Arts Festival Fringe.\n* Anxiety and Grace. With Julia Skeen. 2016. National Arts Festival Fringe and Spiritfest.\n*Epiphanies. With Julia Skeen. 2018. National Arts Festival Fringe and Spiritfest.\n\n===Articles===\n* {{cite journal|last1=Mann|first1=Chris|title=The Guttural Muse in the Sky: A valediction for Seamus Heaney|journal=English Academy Review|volume=30|issue=2|year=2013|pages=129\u2013132|issn=1013-1752|doi=10.1080/10131752.2013.843906|display-authors=0}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Mann|first1=Chris|title=Saturnalia satirica: six satires wearing masks|journal=Scrutiny2|volume=19|issue=1|year=2014|pages=147\u2013151|issn=1812-5441|doi=10.1080/18125441.2014.906257|display-authors=0}}\n*\"Creation and translation.\" Ileana Dimitriu & Chris Mann. Current Writing, Volume 19, 2007 - Issue 1 <ref>{{Cite journal|doi=10.1080/1013929x.2007.9678260|title = Creation and translation|journal = Current Writing|volume = 19|pages = 21\u201352|year = 2007|last1 = Dimitriu|first1 = Ileana|last2 = Mann|first2 = Chris}}</ref>\n*\"Seeing the cosmos in a grain of sand.\" Chris Mann. Current Writing, Volume 20, 2008 - Issue 2 <ref>{{Cite journal|doi=10.1080/1013929x.2008.9678304|title = Seeing the cosmos in a grain of sand|journal = Current Writing|volume = 20|issue = 2|pages = 108\u2013126|year = 2008|last1 = Mann|first1 = Chris}}</ref>\n*\"The Poetry of Belonging. Episodic Memory and Italian and South African Shades.\" English Literature | 3 | 2016 <ref>{{Cite journal|title=The Poetry of Belonging|journal=English Literature|url=http://edizionicafoscari.unive.it/riviste/english-literature/2016/1numero-monografico/the-poetry-of-belonging/|language=en|doi=10.14277/2420-823x/el-3-16-1|last1=Mann|first1=Chris|year=2016}}</ref>\n*\"Points of Illumination: Wordfest South Africa This Year and Next.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pensouthafrica.co.za/points-of-illumination-wordfest-south-africa-this-year-and-next/|title=Points of Illumination: Wordfest South Africa This Year and Next {{!}} PEN South Africa|last=LindsayC|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-10}}</ref>\n\n== Commentary on Mann's Work ==\n\nMann's work has received critical consideration in journals such as\n* ''The English Academy Review'';{{Sfn|Brown|2011|pp=64\u201372}}{{Sfn|Brown|2007|pp=134\u2013137}}{{Sfn|Johnson|1996|pp=75\u2013102}}{{Sfn|Gardner|1995|pp=99\u2013107}}{{Sfn|Foley|1991|pp=15\u201329}}{{Sfn|Butler|1985|pp=163\u2013176}}\n* ''English in Africa'';{{Sfn|Mehuizen|2007|pp=133\u2013140}}\n* ''Shakespeare in Southern Africa'';{{Sfn|Gagiano|2009|pp=95\u201398}}\n* ''Scrutiny2'';{{Sfn|Levey|2010|pp=55\u201369}} and\n* ''Literator''.\n\n== Awards ==\n\n* Newdigate Prize for Poetry while a Rhodes Scholar at Oxford. \n* Olive Schreiner Prize for South African Poetry in English. \n* South African Performing Arts Councils\u2019 Playwright Award. \n* Hon.D.Litt. University of Durban-Westville, now University of KwaZulu-Natal.\n* Eastern Cape Premier\u2019s Award for Literature. \n* First Professor of Poetry, Rhodes University.\n* English Academy of South Africa Thomas Pringle Award for Poetry. \n* Mann's 2014 play ''The Ballad of Dirk de Bruin'' which premiered at the [[National Arts Festival]] was awarded a Silver [[Standard Bank]] Ovation Award for \"artistic innovation, excellence and the exploration of new performance styles\".{{Sfn|Cue|6 July 2014|p=19}}{{Sfn|Grocotts|2014}}\n* Honorary Artist in Residence, Grahamstown Cathedral (2017 - present)\n*Guest poet, Incroci di civilt\u00e0 international poetry festival, Venice 2019\n*English Academy of South Africa Gold Medal 2019\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist|20em}}\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n\n* {{cite book|last=Eve|first=Jeanette |title=A Literary Guide to the Eastern Cape: Places and the Voices of Writers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uwFXGL059QgC&pg=PA136|accessdate=16 September 2013|year=2003|publisher=Juta and Company Ltd|isbn=978-1-919930-15-2|ref= harv}}\n* {{Cite journal\n| last1=Butler\n| first1=G.\n| year=1985\n| title=English and the English in the New South Africa\n| journal=English Academy Review\n| volume=3\n| issue=1\n| pages=163\u2013176\n| doi=10.1080/10131758585310141\n| ref=harv\n }}\n* {{Cite journal\n| last1=Foley\n| first1=A.\n| year=1991\n| title=The white English-speaking South Africans: 'Bastards', 'Wimps', 'Ghosts with ears', or something else again?\n| journal=English Academy Review\n| volume=8\n| issue=1\n| pages=15\u201329\n| doi=10.1080/10131759185310041\n| ref=harv\n }}\n* {{Cite journal\n| last1=Johnson\n| first1=A.\n| year=1996\n| title='The president waves back': Twelve recent books of poetry\n| journal=English Academy Review\n| volume=13\n| issue=1\n| pages=75\u2013102\n| doi=10.1080/10131759685310091\n| ref=harv\n }}\n* {{Cite journal\n| last1=Gardner\n| first1=C.\n| year=19